Who on average has more friends: men or women?

Response: the median and mean friend_count for women is bigger, so women have more friends than men.

What’s the difference between the median friend count for women and men?

Response: 96-74= 22

Why would the median be a better measure than the mean?

Response:

mean for friend_count is bigger than median for both male and female, it makes sense because our data is long-tailed.so these higher value out are gonna pull our mean to the right. so, the median is better measure than mean is, because its more robust statistics. few people with high number of friend_count would drag the mean upward, which is not the necessary representative of most users. what is nice that median is resistent to change since its halfway of the data points. so as long as we trust halfway value we can report our reliable location of the center of distribution. ***

Tenure

Notes: How many days someone has been using facebook. The parameter color determines the color outline of objects in a plot. The parameter fill determines the color of the area inside objects in a plot. You might notice how the color black and the hex code color of #099DD9 (a shade of blue) are wrapped inside of I(). The I() functions stand for ‘as is’ and tells qplot to use them as colors.

qplot(x= tenure, data=fb, binwidth=30, color=I('black'), fill=I('#099DD9'))
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

Transforming Data

Notes: some users have ten times or hundred times the median value. or some people have order of magnitude more likes, click, post and comments than any other users. in statistics we say that data is over-dispersed. we can transform the function or variable so we get rid of long tail, such as log10,2 or square root.in doing so, it helps us to see pattern more clearly

qplot(data=fb, x=friend_count)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

summary(fb$friend_count)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0    31.0    82.0   196.4   206.0  4923.0

#lets trandform it

summary(log10(fb$friend_count))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    -Inf   1.491   1.914    -Inf   2.314   3.692

some of our users have friend_count of zero, so when you take log of that, it will go infinity. to get rid of infinity lets add 1 log10 has been easier as it compares friend_count on order of magnitude of 10

summary(log10(fb$friend_count+1))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.000   1.505   1.919   1.868   2.316   3.692

#another way transforming

summary(sqrt(fb$friend_count))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.000   5.568   9.055  11.088  14.353  70.164

#Plot all trasnformation

#method1 to multiple plots into one

library(gridExtra)
p1=qplot(data=fb, x=friend_count)
p2=qplot(data=fb, x=log10(friend_count+1))
p3=qplot(data=fb, x=sqrt(friend_count))
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3, ncol=1)

*** ### Frequency Polygons frequency polygons (geom_freqpoly()) displays the counts with lines. Frequency polygons are more suitable when you want to compare the distribution across the levels of a categorical variable.

Note that the shape of the frequency polygon depends on how our bins are set up - the height of the lines are the same as the bars in individual histograms, but the lines are easier to make a comparison with since they are on the same axis.

qplot(data=subset(fb, !is.na(gender)), x=friend_count , binwidth=10)+
  scale_x_continuous(lim=c(0,1000), breaks=seq(0,1000,5))+
  facet_wrap(~gender)
## Warning: Removed 2949 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (geom_bar).

###lets apply freqpolgon on the gender so we can compare both disrtribution in line

Note that sum(..count..) will sum across color, so the proportions displayed are based on total users. To plot these proportions within each group, you can try y = ..density…

qplot(data=subset(fb, !is.na(gender)), x=friend_count, y=..count../sum(..count..), binwidth=10,
      xlab='Friend_count',
      ylab='Proportion of Users with that Friend count',
      geom='freqpoly', color=gender)+
  scale_x_continuous(lim=c(0,1000), breaks=seq(0,1000,5))
## Warning: Removed 2949 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).
## Warning: Removed 4 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

###Lets play with the above graph so we can conclude where women takeover men.

qplot(data=subset(fb, !is.na(gender)), x=friend_count, y=..count../sum(..count..), binwidth=10,
      xlab='Friend_count',
      ylab='Proportion of Users with that Friend count',
      geom='freqpoly', color=gender)+
  scale_x_continuous(lim=c(200,800), breaks=seq(0,1000,50))

lets change the above plot to more convenient plot for finding outliers. we always assign numerical(continous) variable on yaxis and categorical on x-axis in plotting boxplot.

qplot(geom = 'boxplot', y= friend_count, x=gender, data=subset(fb, !is.na(gender)))

Adjust the code to focus on users who have friend counts between 0 and 1000.

qplot(geom = 'boxplot', ylim=c(0,1000),
      y= friend_count, x=gender, 
      data=subset(fb, !is.na(gender)))
## Warning: Removed 2949 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

##or

qplot(geom = 'boxplot', data=subset(fb, !is.na(gender)),
      y= friend_count, x=gender )+
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,1000))
## Warning: Removed 2949 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

the problem ylimit or scale_y_continous(limit()) is this that they are removing the data or rows.and it doesnt give us the real box plot. the better approach for that is that we use cartisan:

qplot(geom = 'boxplot', data=subset(fb, !is.na(gender)),
      y= friend_count, x=gender )+ coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0,1000))

It looks like that female have more friends than men as the median bar is above than the men.

Getting Logical

Notes: we understood some of the trasnfoeming variable approach. we often want to convert variable that have lots of zero values to a new binary variable that only have true or false: this is helpful, because we may wanna know weather user have used certian feature or not instead of times says the user have used the feature.

summary(fb$mobile_likes)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0     0.0     4.0   106.1    46.0 25111.0

Response: the median is 4 which means we have lots of dataset with zero. lets use comparison operator.

summary(fb$mobile_likes>0)
##    Mode   FALSE    TRUE 
## logical   35056   63947
fb$mobile_check_in11= NA
fb$mobile_check_in11= ifelse(fb$mobile_likes>0 ,1,0)
fb$mobile_check_in11= factor(fb$mobile_check_in11)
summary(fb$mobile_check_in11)
##     0     1 
## 35056 63947

Note:checking the summer of above we can say that around 64000 are shy of that and checked in heri mobile phones. lets find the percenage of those who used mobile.

sum(fb$mobile_check_in11==1)/length(fb$mobile_check_in11)
## [1] 0.6459097

65% of check in using mobile. its important to understant what kind of data we are looking at. not all transformation are functional, some are like the above example of check in as binary transformation.
